    "25719137": {
      "title": "Interaction between prelanding activities and stiffness regulation of the knee joint musculoskeletal system in the drop jump: implications to performance",
      "abstract": "The purpose of the present study was to investigate the interaction between the pre-landing activities and the stiffness regulation of the knee joint musculoskeletal system and the takeoff speed during a drop jump (DJ). Nine healthy male subjects performed a DJ test from the height of 50 cm. The surface electromyographic (EMG) activity of the vastus lateralis (VL) muscle was recorded to evaluate both the pre-landing and post-landing muscle activation levels. Simultaneous recording of the jumping motion and ground reaction force was performed by a high-speed video camera (100 frames·s–1), and a force platform was employed to allow joint moment analysis. Joint stiffness was calculated by a linear regression of the knee joint moment/angle relationship. Elasticity of the knee extensor muscle during DJ was estimated by means of a four-element muscle model consisting of a parallel elastic component, a series elastic component (SEC), a viscous damper, and a contractile element. DJ performance correlated positively with the positive peak power of the knee joint (P<0.01) and with the moment of the knee joint at the end of stretch (P<0.01). However, there was no significant relationship between DJ performance and the positive peak power of the ankle joint. The knee joint moment at the end of stretch correlated with the SEC stiffness during the transmission phase from the end of the initial impact to the onset of the concentric action (P<0.01) and with the maximum rate of isometric force development of the knee extensors (P<0.01). Multiple regression analysis showed that the SEC stiffness during the transmission phase of the knee joint can be explained by a combination of the pre-activity of the VL muscle and the knee joint angular velocity at touchdown (F=5.76, P<0.05). These results seem to emphasize the functional significance of the pre-programmed activity for controlling the subsequent stiffness regulation and then contributing to the performance in DJ. Thus, it can be suggested that the centrally pre-programmed activity and the associated elastic behavior of the SEC in the knee extensor muscle in conjunction with the muscle contractile property play a major role in regulating the performance in DJ."
    },
    "2812195": {
      "title": "Stretch reflex distinguished from preprogrammed muscle activations following landing impacts in man",
      "abstract": "The landing movement is a convenient model for the study of several fundamental aspects of motor control, one of which is the interaction between central programming and stretch reflexes. When a human or an animal jumps down from a height there is an increase in the amplitude of the activation of leg muscles during the flight phase (Greenwood & Hopkins, 1976; Santello & McDonagh, 1998) prior to impact with the ground. The amplitude of this activity is proportional to the height of the fall and is timed to the moment of impact (Prochazka et al. 1977; Santello & McDonagh, 1998). It is generally accepted that the electromyographic (EMG) activity immediately preceding impact does not arise from a reflex and is pre-programmed in origin (Melvill Jones & Watt, 1971; Santello & McDonagh, 1998). The present experiments investigate the origin of the activity that occurs after impact, which is still a matter of dispute. Some authors have concluded that the activity is weak (Melvill Jones & Watt, 1971; McKinley et al. 1983) or pre-programmed (Dyhre-Poulsen & Laursen, 1984; Dyhre-Poulsen et al. 1991). Others have suggested that it is a reflex response (Greenwood & Hopkins, 1976; Prochazka et al. 1977; Dietz et al. 1981). ::: ::: The purpose of the present experiments was to clearly distinguish the reflex components of the response. The subjects jumped down onto a floor below. The electromyogram (EMG) and joint rotation records taken after passage through a false surface were compared with the records taken when the subject executed another landing to a solid surface at the same distance below. Previous studies have had several shortcomings. First, subjects experienced an unexpectedly lengthened landing distance more than once (Greenwood & Hopkins, 1976). Thus in all trials after the first, a false surface may have been correctly anticipated, or anticipated when not presented or not anticipated when presented. If such trials are averaged together (e.g. Dietz & Noth, 1981) then the true result may become smeared out by differences in response between these conditions, for example differences in the time point at which a programme is switched on and off. Second, one foot reached the ground first when stepping down, allowing the possibility that it was lowered by the supporting leg on the upper stair (Greenwood & Hopkins, 1976). Third, the height of the step down may not have been great enough to evoke a strong reflex response (Greenwood & Hopkins, 1976). Fourth, the time between the false and the real floor was too short to determine whether the programmed activity ended prior to impact (Dyhre-Poulsen & Laursen, 1984). ::: ::: To avoid these shortcomings, the present study was arranged so that each of the subjects experienced the surprise landing condition only once, a two-footed landing movement was used, the height was sufficient to produce high impact forces and the time elapsed between the false and real floor was long enough to reveal the later stages of the programmed activity."
    },
    "96422331": {
      "title": "The mechanics of the backward giant circle on the high bar",
      "abstract": "Abstract In Men's Artistic Gymnastics the backward giant circle on the high bar is used to generate the rotation that the gymnast needs to perform the release–regrasp and dismount skills. Bauer presented a point mass model of high bar circling which indicated that ideally a gymnast should flex around the lowest point and extend around the highest point of a giant circle in order to maximise the increase in energy [cf. Bauer, W. L. (1983). In H. Matsui, K. Kobayashi, Biomechanics VIII-B (pp. 801–806). Champaign, IL: Human Kinetics]. In practice gymnasts follow this technique in only a general sense and flex after the lowest point and extend before the highest point. A four segment planar simulation model of a gymnast was developed to investigate these differences in technique. The model comprised arm, torso, thigh and leg segments with a damped linear spring connecting the arm and torso segments. The high bar was also modelled as a damped linear spring. The model was driven using time histories of hip and shoulder angles. It was found that the simplifications introduced into Bauer's model by neglecting segmental inertias and the elastic characteristics of the gymnast and the bar were not responsible for the differences between the ideal technique and the typical technique of gymnasts. The technique differences could be accounted for by limitations on the torques that are exerted at the shoulder and hip."
    }
  },
